For a moment, he was overwhelmed by the sudden appearance and high morale of the opposition. However, the Imperial Soldiers, the subordinates of the "Tiger Hunter", were not low enough in strength to be beaten by such projectiles.

Above all, the wear and tear on Gudda and his men was almost minimal as far as this battlefield was concerned.

The Imperial Capital had been under tremendous siege, but the harsh attacks made against the other bastions had little effect on this fourth bastion.

This was undoubtedly the achievement of Olbart Dunkelkenn, who reigned as the guardian of the fourth bastion, and was a true demonstration of "The Wily Old Man".

???: [In the first place, it's a good idea to cut off the opponent's legs before you reach here. It's a basic rule of warfare that you cut off what you can't fight without, whether it's water or weapons.]

“The Wily Old Man”, who described the reason why the enemy's offensive was overwhelmingly weak compared to other bastions, had a cruelty that sent chills down the spines of generals at the fear of not being an ally.

However, even Olbart would have had to rush to the other bastions to fulfil his role of protecting the Imperial Capital if they were about to be overtaken.

Therefore, the current fourth bastion lacked the power of the Nine Divine Generals, the greatest strength of the Empire.

Olbart's legacy, his trained superhuman Shinobi, must deal with the flying dragon squadrons that had appeared from the same western sky as the approaching army.

Since they did not have flying weapons, Shinobi's techniques were their only means of defending themselves against the flying dragon squadron.

And for the group that rushed in fiercely――,

Gudda: [――I will give it my all!]

With these words, Gudda Dialmo stared at the enemy in front of him, carrying two metal clubs, each weighing nearly a hundred kilograms, which were synonymous with the nickname "Tiger Hunter”.

Gudda's alias was attributed to the fact that when he was still a General Third-Class, he destroyed a group of tiger men who were committing tyranny in the country, and took the head of the enemy general who had killed the two generals who were in command.

As a result of that fierce battle, Gudda's muscular body, over two meters long, was marked from head to belly with white tiger claw marks, and he came to be known as the "Tiger Hunter" after the fierce battles he had fought.

Gudda's will to fight remained unshaken even as his army was on the verge of collapse after his "general" was killed.

Then, who would be afraid of him when he was outnumbered and had something to bear behind him?

Gudda: [We're coming for you!]

Gudda's huge body kicked the earth and closed in on the enemy horde, his voice like a volley of gunfire.

Following Gudda's lead, his subordinates, carrying their weapons of choice, rushed toward the starry flag that was coming from the west.

Gudda: [――That one.]

As he approached the moment of impact with his own feet, Gudda looked closely and saw the lead of the enemy―― a red gale horse that was passing in front of the group, causing the ground to rumble.

What caught his attention was not the man pulling the reins of the gale horse. The man was only a reinsman, and what should be seen was a small being riding the gale horse as if held by the man.

A black-haired boy who was holding a girl in his arms and looking straight at them with dark eyes.

The boy was neither running ahead nor deviating from his position, but was charging forward as if it were natural for him to be in that position.

A boy with black hair and black eyes, the "black-haired crown prince" who had been talked about before the war started.

